s -- tBibliography -- tIndex rerum -- tIndex locorum 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs a genre situated at the crossroad of rhetoric and fiction, declamatio offers the freedom to experiment with new forms of discourse. Placing the literariness of declamatio into the spotlight, this volume showcases declamation as a realm of genuine literary creation with its own theoretical underpinning, literary technique and generic conventions. Focusing on the oeuvre of (Ps)Quintilian, this volume demonstrates that these texts constitute a genre on their own, the rhetorical and literary framework of which remains not yet fully mapped. It is of interest to students and scholars of Rhetoric and Roman Literature.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aRhetoric, Ancient. 4aDeklamation. 4aLateinische Literatur. 4aLatin literature. 4aQuintilian. 4aRhetorik. 4aRoman declamation. 4arhetoric. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aDinter, Martin T., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGuérin, Charles, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMartinho, Marcos, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2015z9783110438604oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97831103877730 cprintz978311035240540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311035251140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110352511423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110352511.jpg  a978-3-11-070100-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACK